## Scope

This slice adds the Office‑style ribbon‑and‑menu shell as the new front
door and surfaces the standard element catalogue. The ribbon
(`Ribbon.fs`) presents task tabs whose controls are generated from the
centralized command registry (slice 005, `Commands.fs`); when collapsed the
same entries expand into full drop‑down menus, so a command added once to the
registry appears in both with no second wiring site (constraint 0.4). The
contextual Element tab is appended when an element is selected. The
constructor becomes a top‑level page and the default landing page; a *Legacy*
entry opens the present dockable‑panel main screen. The catalogue surfaces
the Part F roles and the value‑id binding action opens a working empty modal.
`LocalHelp.fs` provides context‑sensitive help whose text resolves through
`Localization.fs` (slice 003).

The spec‑writer's hidden‑controls checklist (LLM‑profile select,
web‑search‑provider select, session token counters, `.specrc.agent`
dropdown) does **not** apply: Berreman is an Avalonia F# desktop application
with no `nav.html` and none of those controls.

## Requirements

### R-1. Ribbon tab set (D.1)

D.1.1 A new module
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/Ribbon.fs` MUST define
the ribbon as a set of task tabs. The starting tab set MUST be: **Build**
(place elements and groups), **Element** (edit the active element),
**Trace / View** (rays, zoom, table view, reset, show‑CR toggle),
**Experiment** (groups, collections, detectors), and **Settings**
(language, units, controls, help).

D.1.2 Each ribbon tab's controls MUST be generated from the centralized
command registry (Part E), not hand‑placed per tab, so a command added to
the registry appears on its tab automatically.

### R-2. Collapsible ribbon ↔ full menus (D.2)

D.2.1 The ribbon MUST be collapsible to reclaim screen space. When
collapsed, the same top‑level entries MUST expand into full drop‑down menus
that expose **everything** the ribbons offer. No command MUST be reachable
only from a ribbon or only from a menu — both MUST be projections of the
one command set (constraint 0.4). A command added to the registry MUST
appear in both the ribbon and the menus with no second wiring site.

D.2.2 Office‑style multi‑state collapse (full ribbon → titles‑and‑tabs →
tabs only) MAY be implemented as a progression but is a design detail, not
a fixed requirement; the firm requirement is the single‑source ribbon↔menu
equivalence of D.2.1.

### R-3. Contextual element tab (D.3)

D.3.1 A contextual ribbon tab for the active element MUST appear when an
element is selected and MUST be **appended** beside the persistent tabs
rather than taking over the whole ribbon.

### R-4. Bilingual layout robustness (D.4)

D.4.1 The ribbon and menus MUST remain legible under both EN and RU
strings, which differ in length (Cyrillic labels tend to run longer). The
layout MUST flex rather than truncate when a label is longer in one
language.

### R-5. Legacy menu entry (D.5)

D.5.1 A **Legacy** menu entry MUST open the present dockable‑panel main
screen as‑is (the Construction and Synthesis/Fit pages, `Page` of
Shell.fs:73, laid out by `constructionBody`, Shell.fs:572). The legacy form
is a reference and fallback; it MUST remain reachable and functional but
MUST NOT be required to evolve in lock‑step with the new screen.

### R-6. The constructor is the front door (D.6)

D.6.1 The new constructor screen MUST be a top‑level page and MUST be the
default landing page when the app starts. The existing `Page` union
(Shell.fs:73) MUST be extended with the constructor page, and the nav /
shell entry MUST be wired through the existing root message path
(`RootMsg`, Shell.fs:121) so navigation stays single‑sourced.

### R-7. Reuse before invention for the shell (D.7)

Extend the existing `Page` union (Shell.fs:73) and route through the
existing `RootModel`/`RootMsg` (Shell.fs:94/:121) rather than building a
parallel navigation system. Reuse the dock‑edge seam (`AppShell.toDock`,
AppShell.fs:89) for any docked sub‑panels of the constructor.

### R-8. Catalogue names (F.1)

F.1.1 The catalogue MUST surface these roles, each mapping through
`CatalogueKind.toConstructorElement` (A.5.2): **Optical Table (OT)** (the
workspace itself, Part C), **Light Source (LS)**, **Linear Polarizer (LP)**,
**Circular Polarizer (CP)**, **Sample (S)**, **Lens**, **Flat Mirror**,
**Curved Mirror**, **Detector (D)**. Mirrors, lenses, prisms, and wedges are
the elements that make the side rays meaningful (Part B) and are needed for
focusing and dispersive setups.

F.1.2 A polarizer MUST be just a polarizer regardless of where it sits;
there MUST be no separate "analyzer" catalogue entry and no special label
for a polarizer that follows the sample. The catalogue MUST allow more than
two polarizers in a chain.

### R-9. Value‑id binding action (placeholder) (F.2)

F.2.1 The element's local menu MUST expose an action to open the value‑id
binding. For the first build this action MUST open a functioning **empty
modal dialog** (a fully working, dismissible modal with no picker content).

F.2.2 The real device/material picker behind that dialog is out of scope
for this spec (constraint 0.6). The committed deliverable is the working
menu action and the working empty modal; this is a complete end state, not
a stub — the id slot (A.6) and the menu entry exist so nothing is
retro‑fitted later.

### R-10. Reuse before invention for the catalogue (F.3)

Map catalogue kinds onto the existing `ConstructorElement` cases
(BeamTree.fs:35) via the A.5.2 function; do not add new element DU cases for
LP/CP (they are `Polarizer`) and do not remove `Analyzer` (BeamTree.fs:42).

### R-11. Discoverability UX commitment (UX 1)

The constructor is a new top‑level page and the default landing page (D.6);
its nav/shell entry is added to the existing `Page` union (Shell.fs:73) and
marked active with distinct styling like the current `navButton`
(Shell.fs:500). The *Legacy* entry (D.5) opens the present dockable‑panel
main screen (`constructionBody`, Shell.fs:572).

## Non-requirements

- No real device/material picker behind the value‑id modal (0.6, F.2.2) —
  only the working menu action + empty modal.
- No removal of the `Analyzer` DU case and no new LP/CP DU cases
  (BeamTree.fs:42, F.3).
- The legacy dockable screen MUST remain reachable but MUST NOT be evolved
  in lock‑step with the new screen (D.5.1).
- No element‑group / experiment‑collection behaviour behind the *Experiment*
  tab (Part G/H / slice 007) — the tab exists and projects its commands from
  the registry, but the group/collection semantics land in slice 007.

